Dig your post holes deep enough to bury half the pole. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/95/Fence-a-Garden-Step-3Bullet2-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Fence-a-Garden-Step-3Bullet2-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/95/Fence-a-Garden-Step-3Bullet2-Version-2.jpg/v4-760px-Fence-a-Garden-Step-3Bullet2-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Add gravel to cover the bottom of the hole before setting the post. This will help with drainage. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3a/Fence-a-Garden-Step-3Bullet3-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Fence-a-Garden-Step-3Bullet3-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3a/Fence-a-Garden-Step-3Bullet3-Version-2.jpg/v4-760px-Fence-a-Garden-Step-3Bullet3-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

When using dirt, make sure you continuously compress the dirt as you add it to the hole. This makes for a solid, tight fit. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ee/Fence-a-Garden-Step-5Bullet1-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Fence-a-Garden-Step-5Bullet1-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ee/Fence-a-Garden-Step-5Bullet1-Version-2.jpg/v4-760px-Fence-a-Garden-Step-5Bullet1-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you choose cement as your base, you will need to stabilize the post until the cement sets. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/54/Fence-a-Garden-Step-5Bullet2-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Fence-a-Garden-Step-5Bullet2-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/54/Fence-a-Garden-Step-5Bullet2-Version-2.jpg/v4-760px-Fence-a-Garden-Step-5Bullet2-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

A simple gate can be made by extending the length of the materials used approximately 1 foot (0.3 meters). {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0e/Fence-a-Garden-Step-7Bullet1-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Fence-a-Garden-Step-7Bullet1-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0e/Fence-a-Garden-Step-7Bullet1-Version-2.jpg/v4-760px-Fence-a-Garden-Step-7Bullet1-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Add some hooks onto the extension in order to attach the gate to the fence when you want it closed. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0c/Fence-a-Garden-Step-7Bullet2-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Fence-a-Garden-Step-7Bullet2-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0c/Fence-a-Garden-Step-7Bullet2-Version-2.jpg/v4-760px-Fence-a-Garden-Step-7Bullet2-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
